`scripts/` is the repo's CI static-check suite: a set of independent, single-purpose pass/fail scripts enforcing the policies in docs/SPEC.md (no unused deps, no bare `#[allow]`, workspace-wide lint inheritance, function/file size limits) plus two placeholders reserved for future dylint rules. Depending on this directory means running these as gates in CI; each script exits 0/1 with no other side effects and no shared state between them.

All git-enumerating scripts (`no_allow_check.sh`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh` indirectly via cd+external tool, `rationale_check.py`) use `git ls-files --cached --others --exclude-standard` rather than a filesystem walk, specifically to avoid racing concurrent `target/` writes and to get `.gitignore` pruning for free — this is a deliberate cross-script convention, not per-file happenstance; if one script's enumeration logic changes, check the others for consistency. Failure output convention is also shared: `FAIL: ` prefixed lines to stderr, `path:line` format where applicable (grep-forced multi-file mode in `no_allow_check.sh`) matching what ctx-verify's parser expects.

Two scripts are explicit non-functional placeholders pending dylint rules (see docs/DYLINT_RULES.md): `cycle_check.sh` only checks that `cargo-modules` runs, never that cycles are absent; `rationale_check.py` uses heuristic brace-counting rather than AST parsing and is scoped as an MVP stand-in. `machete_check.sh` and `workspace_lints_check.sh` are the two scripts enforcing hard, always-on policies with no waiver mechanism. `no_allow_check.sh` similarly has no suppression path by design (pre-MVP).

A caller integrating these into CI must not conflate `cycle_check.sh`'s exit code with actual cycle-freedom — that's the one cross-script trap that isn't obvious from any single script's contract.